A somber and experimental guest mix from produder and DJ Maral – featuring Iranian classics, early shellac recordings of Iranian classical Music, and field recordings of folk music from different regions of Iran.
Tapping into the liminal feelings of being in the diaspora, mixtures of sadness, anger, fear and nostalgia. A cathartic mix for anyone in the world.
The Stockholm-born composer and pianist shares another suite of sounds – contemporary and classical compositions, electronic productions, and leftfield indie sounds.

Few artists have straddled the worlds of jazz, R&B, funk, and soul as confidently as Roy Ayers – ask four people what genre he's known for and you may receive four different answers. 
Beyond being a world-class vibraphonist, and penning the life-affirming anthem "Everybody Love The Sunshine", Ayers life and music was rich with diversions – touring with Fela Kuti, performing with Whitney Houston, countless studio collaborations, and endless innovation on his solo records. 
Selected and mixed by Suncut.
Renowned Italian soundtrack composer Fabio Frizzi, famous for his work on horror films The Beyond, Zombi 2 and more takes over, selecting an hour of musical inspirations.

Musical selections from the filmography of Parker Posey, dubbed "Queen of the Indies" starring in numerous independent films from the early 1990s onwards. Including sounds from Dazed & Confused, Flirt, Party Girl, The White Lotus and more. 
Selected and mixed by Florence Scott-Anderton.

nts1.n: NTS GUIDE TO: MUSIC FROM JAPAN’S CD-ERA ELECTRONIC UNDERGROUND (R)
nts1.d:
A journey through Japan’s quietly radical independent underground of the late ‘90s and early 2000s. Drawn from small-run CDs, obscure compilations, and deeply interconnected label networks, reflecting a moment where ambient, glitch, IDM, and experimental club sounds flourished into new forms — shaped by a generation of artists working across clubs, galleries, and record shops.
Created by Cameron Cullen

nts2.n: Return to Paradise w/ Forces From Above
nts2.d:
Something happened to me this past summer… I encountered the peaceful bliss that is the music of Exotica for the first time. I become so fixated on its relaxing and hypnotic beauty that it became this paradise of sound that I returned to again and again.
In the late 1950’s, Martin Denny ditched his orchestral, Big Band sound to create what would be known as the “Exotica” genre. Combining the music of lounge jazz with tropical flavors from the Hawaiian & Caribbean islands, he birthed something uniquely experiential for its time. While it was despised by critics during its era, it became a hit within tiki bars and beach side resorts, it later brought about a cult following. Other artists in Denny’s circle joined and made it in their own vision. With the sounds of bird calls, animals howling, and ocean waves crashing, you get a cinematic experience with every song. This mix is a curated journey through this forgotten time in music. Welcome back to paradise.
Calling on all higher powers for some peace of mind <3

A mix of songs inspired by small moments in my life. Petting a cat on the street, listening to a stranger's story in a café, watching the snails cross the footpath on a rainy day and flowing with the trees in the wind. For me, peace isn't always still, it's about escaping into a new perspective and sharing our presence with everything we pass.

this mix is filled with timeless, spiritual jazz masterpieces that symbolise gravitation towards states of peace, harmony and love within ourselves and ultimately - humanity as a whole. "take it from me, someday we'll all be free" - donny hathaway
Peace is letting the red balloon go, watching it move through the room beyond tomorrow.

I wasn't sure how to interpret the theme 'peace'. My first thought was: my personal feeling of 'peacefulness' which is connected to how I feel in a space - at home, with loved ones. Then I thought of a more global, political understanding of peace. And here, I am undecided: is global / political peace a feeling of safety, calmness, love as I am lucky enough to experience personally ? Is it connected to emotions or factualities ?

nts2.n: Hour of the Wolf w/ Coco Lova
nts2.d:
A mix inspired by the hour of the wolf. The expression comes from the
Nordic folklore and refers to the time before dawn - a space of
unconsciousness, obscurity, and vivid dreams. The selection moves through
ambient and electronic soundscapes, with traces of folk.

nts2.d: Imagine this: you walk through the city and let these songs come to you like intrusive thoughts — fragments of peace, mental noise, and everything in between.

The Doukhobors are a pacifist Christian movement. They immigrated to Canada in 1899, fleeing persecution for their pacifist beliefs in the Russian Empire. This is a mix of their traditional a capella choral singing, rarely available online, reflecting their history and enduring call for peace.

nts2.n: PEACE, LOVE AND UNITY W/ AUSTIN MOULTON
nts2.d: The show features rare groove, gospel and soul tracks promoting the core message of ‘Love, Peace and Unity’. This is music with a message that is just as pertinent today as it was when these songs were released in the 1970s and 80’s.

subtle.d:
DJ & Producer, B-Say has been a Subtle resident DJ for over 3 years.

His radio shows tend to focus on the 140 bass music scene and aims to showcase unreleased/forthcoming music from upcoming artists, as well as premiering his own unreleased material. 

More recently B-Say has ventured out from solely DJ'ing Dubstep, with his bi-monthly 'Dub & Steppers Show' which he uses to premier his own productions.

Slick is a London-based Producer and DJ combining the sounds of Grime and Drill.

Following his widely acclaimed breakout moment winning the 2013 DMC World Online Championships, Jon1st quickly built an international reputation as a ‘DJ’s DJ’. Not only proving himself as one of the world’s most diverse and musical turntablists, Jon also established himself as an on the pulse club DJ mixing across the alternative bass music spectrum and as an in demand live performer around the world, as well as recording acclaimed guest mixes for everyone from DJ Mag to Boiler Room to Ninja Tune’s Solid Steel to Mary Anne Hobbs to Keep Hush.
